**Frame‐by‐Frame Analysis**  
• **Frame 1**: Road ahead is fairly straight, no traffic signals visible. On the right appears to be a sign with a circular arrow pattern, suggesting a roundabout sign.  
• **Frame 2**: The circular‐arrows sign on the right is clearer, and just beneath it is a yield‐triangle shape. No stop signs or traffic lights are evident.  
• **Frame 3**: The same roundabout sign is more noticeable; there are no signals overhead or cross streets that would form a classic T‐junction.  
• **Frame 4**: The roundabout sign and yield sign are in plain view; the roadway ahead veers slightly to the right.  
• **Frame 5**: The lane dividers curve toward what looks like a small traffic circle. Again, no traffic light or stop signs in sight.  

**Contextual Reasoning**  
Across the frames, the signage consistently shows a roundabout diagram and a yield sign. There is no overhead traffic signal, nor are there multiple stop signs indicating an all‐way stop. This is not simply a T‐junction because the signage and roadway design point to a circular intersection.  

**Match to Answer Choices**  
• **A. All Way Stop** – No stop signs are visible, so unlikely.  
• **B. Traffic Light Controlled** – No signals or lights are apparent.  
• **C. T‐junction** – The signage and roadway do not support a pure T‐shaped intersection; also the roundabout sign says otherwise.  
• **D. Roundabout** – The repeated circular‐arrow sign, yield signs, and the roadway layout all point to this.  

<answer>D. Roundabout</answer>
